# Inline table editing (UI convention)

For **Einnahmen**, **Ausgaben**, and **Budget**-style data tables, prefer **inline editing** (row expands in-place, or cells swap to inputs) instead of modal dialogs or bottom sheets for editing existing rows.

## When to use inline patterns

- Editing fields that belong to a single logical row (metadata, amounts, dates, selects).
- Keeping scroll position and surrounding context visible.

## When modals are still acceptable

- **Creating** a new entity when the form is long and would clutter a narrow table (e.g. “new position” sheet on the budget page).
- Flows that need a focused step (confirmations, multi-step wizards) unrelated to a single row.

## Implementation sketch

- Track an `editingId` (or draft object keyed by row id); toggle the row template between read and edit branches (`@if` / `*ngIf`), matching `spendings-page` / `accounts-page` patterns.
- For editable table rows, treat the display row itself as an edit affordance: clicking a non-interactive cell/area of the row should enter inline edit (buttons/links/inputs inside the row keep their own behavior).
- Keep the same column structure between read and edit states. If a column is calculated/non-editable, still render it in edit mode as read-only display (do not replace it with placeholders like `—`).
- For wide grids, a **full-width detail row** under the data row (`colspan` across all columns) is fine if it keeps one concern per row and avoids a modal.

## Examples in this repo

- `spendings-page.component.html` — row switches to inputs; save/cancel in-row.
- `accounts-page.component.html` — inline edit with save/cancel; row click opens edit mode.
- `budget-page.component.html` — planned amounts and one-off **names** as in-cell inputs; **position meta** (category, cadence, dates, planned scope, template reapply) in a **modal** opened from “Edit” or row click (`openEditPositionModal`). Same **Enter** / **OK–Cancel icon** pattern as sheets: see `row-confirm-actions` rule.
